{"type":null,"faqId":26404,"title":"Dark Photos When Taken in Backlight Environments","answer":"<p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:center\" align=\"center\"><b><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';\ncolor:#333333\">Dark Photos When Taken in Backlight Environments</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;text-indent:21.0pt;\n\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:#333333;\n\">The HDR feature can help you take bright photos even in\nbacklight environments. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:#333333;\">[Introduction\nto HDR]</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:#333333;\n\">High Dynamic Range (HDR) helps solve the problem that the\ncamera's dynamic range is restricted when you take photos of objects whose\nbrightest and darkest parts contrast significantly. With HDR, your phone\nprocesses multiple photos with different exposure into one photo with rich dark\nand bright details. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:#333333;\n\">For example, if you take photos of a person in strong\nlight, the person's face look dark in backlight. If you focus on the person's\nface, the background light looks too bright and the face gets blurred. To take\na photo with balanced exposure, enable HDR and focus on the person. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:#333333;\">When should\nwe use HDR?</span></b><span style=\"font-family:'Microsoft YaHei','sans-serif';\ncolor:#333333;\"><br>\n</span><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';\ncolor:#333333;\">Applicable scenarios include but are not\nlimited to portrait in backlight, scenery in strong light (such as the blue\nsky, white clouds, and green grasses), and indoor shooting with strong light\nshining into the window. </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:#333333;\n\">Inapplicable scenarios include but are not limited to\nshooting moving objects or in good light conditions (balanced light without\nabrupt strong lights). </span></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><b><span style=\"\nfont-family:'minorBidi','serif';\">[Tip]</span></b></p>\n<p style=\"margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-size:10.5pt;font-family:'Calibri','sans-serif';text-align:left;\" align=\"left\"><span style=\"font-family:'minorBidi','serif';color:#333333;\n\">When you use HDR, if you do not want the phone to save\nthe original photo and HDR photo simultaneously, go to <b>Settings</b> and turn off the option of saving the photo with normal\nexposure. </span></p>\n<br>\n</p>","faqTypeId":null,"faqType":null,"useful":0,"unUseful":0,"languageId":1,"languageName":"en","faqCode":"783","faqTypeCode":null,"isTop":"0","moduleCode":"faq","productId":null,"productCode":null,"postDate":1433162642000,"seriesProductName":"","visitedTimes":3,"isUsefulFlag":null,"score":0,"times":0,"imageList":null,"displayType":"text","justView":"0","fileName":null,"filePath":null,"imagePath":null,"imageName":null,"productIdList":null,"curPage":null,"pageSize":null,"siteCode":null,"statusFlag":"Publish","returnCode":0,"totalRows":null,"keywords":"Dark Photos When Taken in Backlight Environments","avgScore":0.0,"createDate":null,"totalPages":null}